===Etymology===
Modern Latin, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ἀφασία|lang=grc}}, from {{term|ἄφατος||speechless|lang=grc}}, from {{term|ἀ-||not|lang=grc}} + {{term|φάσις||speech|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈfeɪzɪə/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{context|pathology|lang=en}} A [[partial]] or [[total]] [[loss]] of [[language]] [[skill]]s due to [[brain]] [[damage]]. Usually, damage to the left perisylvian region, including Broca's area and Wernike's area, causes aphasia.
#* '''1888''', [[w:Rudyard Kipling|Rudyard Kipling]], "The Conversion of Aurelian McGoggin" in ''Plain Tales from the Hills'', Folio 2005, p. 76:
#*: The Doctor came over in three minutes, and heard the story.  ‘It's '''''aphasia''''',’ he said.

